<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Remarks</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Mimulus guttatus </i>is an extremely variable annual herb with bright yellow bilabiate flowers, dotted with orange. It is widespread in California and the West. It has been the subject of much evolutionary biology research, largely because it has served as the basal species for the recent evolution of several other taxa, including <i>Mimulus glaucescens, M. nudatus </i>(CNPS list 4.3 plants), and <i>M. pardalis, </i>which are recently derived edaphic endemics (Alexander et al. 2007, Hughes et al. 2001, MacNair and Gardner 1998, Tilstone and MacNair 1997). <br/>
<br/>
The alliance often forms stands within the splash zone of small first-order streams, seeps, springs, and hanging gardens. Stands often occur as small patches or in narrow linear strips, occasionally broadening into small hollows. Some stands occur on very steep cascades and waterfalls, or along gentle streams. The floristic composition of stands is variable. As currently understood, the alliance includes stands with <i>Mimulus guttatus, M. lewisii, M. moschatus, </i>or <i>M. pilosus </i>characteristically present. Stands sometimes occur in mesic upland areas that quickly dry by mid to late spring; they are not usually on flats or in swales, unlike stands of the vernal pool alliances. </div>
</div>

    
	
	
