    <div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
        <h4 class="header">Regional Status</h4>
        
            <p>The range of <i>Mimulus guttatus</i> and other <i>Mimulus</i> spp. include all sections in the state.</p>
        

        <ul class="text">
        
            <li><b>Central California Coast</b> (261Ac, Ae-f, Aj). Stands occur on serpentine in the Diablo Range and on Coyote Ridge. A stand was surveyed at the end of Martini Creek in San Mateo County (Sikes et al. 2021). Stands are probable near Sobrante Creek in Monterey County and near Scott's Valley in Santa Cruz (Calflora 2020).</li>
        
            <li><b>Central California Coast Ranges</b> (M262Aa-c, Ae-f, Ah, Aj). Stands at Pinnacles National Monument (Kittel et al. 2012) and at Fort Hunter-Liggett with <i>M. guttatus</I> and <i>M. pilosus</i> occur at springs, along steep rocky stream banks, and near wet stony outcrops.</li>
        
            <li><b>Great Valley</b> (262Ag, Ao). A <i>Mimulus guttatus</i> stand was sampled above Fahrens Creek, and others are probable on near the banks of the streams in the region.</li>
        
            <li><b>Klamath Mountains</b> (M261Ac, Af, Ai-j, Am, Ar, Au). Stands are common in seeps, in springs, and along steep-gradient streams throughout the section.</li>
        
            <li><b>Modoc Plateau</b> (M261Ga-d, Gf-l, Gn-p). Stands are common in seeps, in springs, and along moderately steep-gradient stream channels (S. Smith 1998b).</li>
        
            <li><b>Northern California Coast</b> (263Ag, Al-m). Stands have been sampled in northern Marin County, in Sonoma County near Sonoma Lake, and in a drainage above Pross Creek (Klein et al 2015), and are probable in other locations in the section.</li>
        
            <li><b>Northern California Coast Ranges</b> (M261Bf). A stand was sampled in a drainage above Knoxville Creek, and stands are probable in other locations (Consortium of California Herbaria 2020).</li>
        
            <li><b>Northern California Interior Coast Ranges</b> (M261Ca-b). Stands in this section occur adjacent to ephemeral watercourses.</li>
        
            <li><b>Sierra Nevada</b> (M261Ef-g, Ep). Stands scattered at lower montane elevations are adjacent to streams, waterfalls, or on floodplains and transitional fens with <i>M. guttatus, M. lewisii,</i> or others that are dominant. Cooper and Wolf (2006) recognized a <i>Mimulus guttatus</i> association in their fen survey. Potter (2005) did not sufficiently sample to recognize associations; instead he recognized both low and mid elevation riparian forb groups with <i>Mimulus</i> spp. dominant.</li>
        
            <li><b>Sierra Nevada Foothills</b> (M261Fa-d). Stands in the northern (Klein et al. 2007) and central and southern subsections (Potter 2005) are mostly small (< 0.25 ha) and adjacent to ephemeral streams and waterfalls. Adjacent vegetation includes <i>Quercus douglasii</i> and <i>Q. lobat</i> a woodlands, as well as herbaceous stands of the <i>Lasthenia glaberrima, Layia fremontii-Achyrachaena mollis, Nassella pulchra, </i> and <i>Lasthenia californica-Plantago erecta-Vulpia microstachys</i> alliances.</li>
        
            <li><b>Southern Cascades</b> (M261Dd-f, Dh-j, Dl-m). Stands with <i>M. guttatus</i> and <i>M. lewisii</i> are common in the section on seeps, springs, stream banks, and other wet places (S. Smith 1998b).</li>
        
        </ul>
    </div>


    
	
<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Management Considerations</h4>
	<div class="text"> Stands are typically small and any impacts to the stream flows or hydrology will influence them. Grazing negatively affects stands with <i>Mimulus guttatus </i>in the Sierra Nevada (Potter 2005). </div>
</div>

    

    

